enzymes","Increases prostacyclin synthesis","Reversibly binds cyclooxygenase enzymes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAspirin works by \u003Cstrong\u003Eirreversibly acetylating cyclooxygenase enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E. It covalently modifies a serine residue in the active site of both cyclooxygenase-1 (COX-1) and cyclooxygenase-2 (COX-2). In platelets, this prevents the formation of thromboxane A2, leading to reduced platelet aggregation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReversibly binds cyclooxygenase enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - Aspirin forms a permanent covalent bond with the enzyme rather than a temporary association.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitively inhibits thromboxane receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Aspirin prevents thromboxane production by inhibiting the enzyme responsible for its synthesis rather than blocking its receptor.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels in platelets\u003C/strong\u003E - Aspirin does not interact with calcium channels but instead works through enzyme inhibition.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases prostacyclin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Aspirin actually decreases prostacyclin production through its inhibition of cyclooxygenase enzymes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBecause platelets cannot synthesise new proteins, the antiplatelet effect of aspirin persists until new platelets are produced (7-10 days). This is particularly important at low doses where aspirin preferentially affects platelet COX-1.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aspirin irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase enzymes by acetylating a serine residue.","Low-dose aspirin selectively inhibits platelet cyclooxygenase-1, reducing thromboxane A2 production.","The antiplatelet effect of aspirin persists for the lifespan of 